label chapter5:

    # [Scene: Seawall Construction Site | Morning]

    scene bg ch5_4001e7_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Bright strings with a steady rhythm — a pulse of accomplishment]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant gulls, the rhythmic thud of tamping tools, the soft clink of metal on metal]
    "You stand at the lip of the finished segment and let the morning wash over you. The smell of wet concrete and seaweed is sharp and honest, the sort of smell that tastes like work done"
    "with hands and feet in the mud. Volunteers move like a low tide line — purposeful, efficient, already folding into the next tasks. For the first time in weeks the harbor's edge reads less like a"
    "wound and more like a repaired seam."
    "Your palm finds the brass compass at your belt out of habit. The metal is cool; it steadies the ache behind your ribs. Momentum is a tactile thing here — sacks of sand stacked in measured"
    "lines, geotextile pinned just so, the living-root bundles waiting for their first bed. You can see the math of it: one careful action, multiplied across bodies."
    "Ronan meets you with a grin that's half pride, half exhaustion. He wipes his hands on his pants and pulls you close to the edge where seedlings will be planted next week."
    show ronan_pike at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ronan_pike "We did good, didn't we? The tide wasn't a monster like last time. Oba said the line is holding."
    show alys_maren at right:
        zoom 0.7

    alys_maren "We did. It held because people showed up. Because you didn't sleep three nights. Because Ivo Calder rammed those piles when the tide changed."
    "Ronan laughs, but his eyes flicker to the far end of the wall, where a thin seam still needs finishing."

    ronan_pike "Think Leyna will be happy with the sediment traps? She keeps sending those charts like they're love letters."

    alys_maren "She writes like she cares about us personally. Which, I suppose, she does."

    ronan_pike "Then let's make her proud. And then you can stop writing in that little book like it's going to save the world."
    "You feel the impulse to protest — the notebook is, in part, a promise — but the remark lands as the gentle joking it is. You tuck the thought away and look out at the line of volunteers who have already started the next pile."

    menu:
        "Walk the finished seam and check the anchors":
            "You run your fingers along the damp concrete, tasting salt on the air, and find small cracks that make a plan for repair spark in your head."
        "Pull Ronan aside and sketch the planting order":
            "You crouch with Ronan, rapid lines of instruction pushed into the dirt, and the two of you carve the next day's work out of urgency and coffee-fueled optimism."

    # --- merge ---
    "The choice feels small — a micro-logic of logistics — but each small choice folds into the larger promise you've been building. You pick one and the morning hum continues: hands in earth, plans in breath."
    # [Scene: North Beach Ridge | Afternoon]
    hide ronan_pike
    hide alys_maren

    scene bg ch5_4001e7_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm acoustic guitar, gentle tempo — hopeful, steady]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Wind singing across dunes, the occasional creak of a slack rope]
    "By the time you reach the ridge, Maya is there with a paint-streaked cap, organizing a stack of salvaged netting. She looks up as you approach and the expression on her face is an inventory of trust: tired, warm, expectant."
    show maya_maren at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_maren "You look like someone who slept enough to know what this looks like."
    show alys_maren at right:
        zoom 0.7

    alys_maren "I'm barely on schedule. But the line—it's holding. People are talking about what comes next."

    maya_maren "That's what scares folks. Fix the hole and someone asks who's paying next week. Who gets the new boats. Who loses the shoreline altogether."
    "You watch a gust lift a thin veil of sand, glittering like glass. The ridge is both placid and fragile — the very tension you live inside."
    "Ivo Calder arrives with his cap low, carrying a coil of rope over his shoulder. His hands smell of rope and engine oil. When he sees you, the face that usually folds easily into humor tightens with something like relief."
    show ivo_calder at center:
        zoom 0.7

    ivo_calder "How did it look from your end?"

    alys_maren "Solid. Ronan's crew did well. Leyna's traps should slow the scouring; we planted the first bundles of root mat near the inlet."

    ivo_calder "Good. Good. People needed a win. They need to see they can trust something that isn't a council promise or a flashy contract."
    "You feel that tug — the core of what this is about. Trust. It has to be both earned and tangible."

    ivo_calder "But Celine Harrow's been calling. She wants to send in contractors to 'expedite' the rest. Says she'll secure municipal funds if we let them do the heavy lifting."
    "Your chest tightens, an old familiar pressure. The word 'contractors' carries as many promises as it does caveats. You think of cheap culverts, concrete poured without care, habitat flattened for speed."

    alys_maren "Contracts mean speed. They also mean decisions not ours."

    ivo_calder "Exactly. And people will look at a paved wall and say 'safe.' They won't see the lost eelgrass, the bulldozed marsh. They'll forget the work that made a living shore possible."
    "The conversation slows into something more intimate — not argument, but negotiation of values."

    alys_maren "I don't want to be the person who says no and lets another storm take us. But I don't want quick fixes that steal the recovery we're trying to breed."

    ivo_calder "So what's the play?"

    alys_maren "We keep pushing community-led for what we can, but… there are places contractors could move faster. Is there a way to accept help without giving everything away?"
    "Ivo Calder studies you. His jaw sets. You sense his loyalty nearest to the bone — to people's roofs, their fisheries, their immediate safety."

    ivo_calder "If we open the door, we need to keep the keys. Oversight. People on the ground. Real contracts with enforceable clauses. No backdoor deals."
    "You nod. It's the third way you had been turning over in your head: not pure resistance, not blind acceptance, but a hybrid tethered by oversight. A compromise is its own art — and beauty to you if it keeps the town's hands in the plan."

    menu:
        "Tell Maya about demanding oversight":
            "Maya's face hardens into pragmatic resolve; she immediately starts drafting a list of what community oversight would look like."
        "Keep the idea between you and Ivo for now":
            "You close your mouth and it feels like holding a delicate seed; Ivo reads your silence and relaxes into the role of someone who will carry the carrying."

    # --- merge ---
    "The day keeps giving you small proofs: seedlings pushed through sand, volunteers laughing when a knot refuses to hold. The ridge breathes with a tempered kind of hope — not naive, but real."
    # [Scene: Harbor — Quay by the Council Docks | Evening]
    hide maya_maren
    hide alys_maren
    hide ivo_calder

    scene bg ch5_4001e7_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low piano with a rising major chord — measured, emissive]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A far bell from the harbor, muffled footsteps, the whisper of the incoming tide]
    "You find Celine Harrow at the same place she watched from before. Her silhouette is precise against the harbor light. Tonight, there is a municipal folder in her hand — the leather sharp, the papers inside"
    "promising solutions. She watches the seawall with a look you have learned to read as 'strategic appraisal.' There is warmth in it, but it is bound by a different geography than the one you inhabit."
    show celine_harrow at left:
        zoom 0.7

    celine_harrow "Alys. The work tonight looks… orderly. Efficient."
    show alys_maren at right:
        zoom 0.7

    alys_maren "We had people who knew what to do. They stayed. That's part of why this line is holding."
    "Celine Harrow smiles, small and diplomatic. You can hear the council meeting beneath everything she says. Her offer is already coiled."

    celine_harrow "Our contractors have done work in similar towns. We can speed this up — bring in heavy lifts, concrete mixers, a funded timeline. It'll be fast, and the town will be protected more quickly. There are grants available now if we act before the budget window closes."
    "Her voice is smooth; the offer is public-minded on the surface. You feel your chest respond to the promise of speed. You also feel something darker: the possibility that speed will overwrite nuance."

    alys_maren "Speed's only useful if we're not trading away the ecosystems that make the coast livable. Contractors don't always account for eelgrass or marsh hydrology."
    "Celine Harrow inclines her head slightly, an expert performing the patient counterbalance."

    celine_harrow "We're not talking about bulldozing wetlands. The contracts would include environmental clauses. We can stipulate oversight. Municipal procurement protocols exist for a reason."
    "You want to believe the clauses, the protocols. You know, though, how language can be shaped after signatures. You're aware of the pressure in her offer: a budget window, a deadline, a town sighing with relief at visible progress."
    "Ivo Calder moves to stand beside you, boots scuffed and hands dug into his pockets. His presence is a different kind of argument — not rhetorical, but physical."
    show ivo_calder at center:
        zoom 0.7

    ivo_calder "If Celine Harrow wants to fast-track, we'd need people in the plan. Real enforcement. Not just nice language."

    celine_harrow "We can do inspections. We can appoint a community liaison."
    "Her eyes flick to yours. For a moment they are complex — not unreadable in a way that suggests mystery, but layered: a leader's calculation underlaid with a human who may fear the town's economic erosion."

    alys_maren "A liaison is only as good as the power they hold. Who appoints them? Who pays legal oversight if something's not done right? Contracts can look good until they're tested."

    celine_harrow "We can negotiate those terms. If your team cannot meet the timeline, people will grow anxious. They'll vote for anything that feels fast. My job is to keep Saltwick solvent."
    "You feel the rooms of her reasoning — budgets, votes, the terrifying arithmetic of livelihoods — pressing against your own. You also think about the faces who will sleep without fear if walls are finished sooner."
    "Maya and Ronan hover a few steps behind you, watching the exchange like a chorus in a play. Their attention feels concentrated into expectation: will you hold the line of community independence, will you take Celine Harrow's hand, or will you try to stitch both together?"
    "You look at the harbor, then at the volunteers who have been sleeping under tarps, feeding children, and keeping watches. You think of Oba's stories about how the tide used to curve, carrying seedlings naturally. You"
    "think of Leyna's graphs, tick marks like fortunes. You think of the town's need for work, for weathered hands to be busy with healing rather than despair."
    "Celine Harrow closes the folder with the faintest of snaps, giving the sound a punctuation that might pass for generosity."

    celine_harrow "I'm not asking you to sign without input. I'm asking you to consider a partnership. It would mean faster completion. Public acclaim, even. You would be lauded for saving Saltwick."

    alys_maren "Public acclaim doesn't plant eelgrass."

    celine_harrow "No — but it buys time, Alys. Time for the seedlings to take, time for the council to secure longer-term budgets. We can draft oversight into the contract."

    ivo_calder "Drafting is easy. Enforcement rarely is. We need people on the ground authorized to stop work if it violates ecological terms."
    "Celine Harrow pauses, appraising. There is a beat where you imagine her flipping through municipal records tucked in that cuff of hers — budgets, precedents, the levers she knows how to pull."

    celine_harrow "Make me a checklist. Tell me what you require for oversight, and we'll see if procurement will allow it. The funds won't wait forever."
    "You feel the hopeful chord swell in your chest. The possibility of a hybrid — funds with enforceable oversight — feels like the pragmatic crescendo you've been chasing. It promises both the speed the town craves and the stewardship you won't trade."
    "But you also feel the practical, merciless tick of time. Negotiations slow things down. Committees, lawyers, clauses — each step could let tide and weather do what they will. You think about the volunteers who slept"
    "two nights under tarps to build a line of protection tonight. You think about the elders who can name every storm by the sound of its rain."
    "The evening air smells like an approaching blessing. The town is watching, literally and figuratively: lamplight glancing off rain-darkened wood, faces upturned."

    ivo_calder "Whatever we choose, we make it ours. We don't let them set the arc and then walk away."
    "You nod. The knot tightens and loosens in your chest: leadership has always been about catching two things that want to fall in different directions and holding them steady enough to stitch."
    "Maya steps forward, voice steady."
    hide celine_harrow
    show maya_maren at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_maren "We can't make this a private negotiation. The people who weather the storms need to be at the table."
    hide alys_maren
    show celine_harrow at right:
        zoom 0.7

    celine_harrow "And they will be. That is part of the plan."
    "Her promise sits in the air like a buoy — visible, but not yet anchored."

    menu:
        "Take out your compass, lay it on the quay, and ask for a formal clause list now":
            "You set the brass compass down between you and Celine like a small altar of intention; the motion turns the negotiation into covenant and everyone falls silent, honoring the gravity of the ask."
        "Keep the compass hidden and ask Celine to draft terms for later":
            "You keep your hands folded, and the night carries a little more uncertainty; Celine nods and pulls a phone from her coat, as if the work can begin without a symbolic sealing."

    # --- merge ---
    "You can feel the town leaning in like a tide. The rising momentum you have helped to create makes the question more urgent — now there is something to lose and something to gain. The air tastes of possibilities: clean, brisk, and charged."
    "Your notebook is in your pocket. Your compass sits beneath fabric if you chose to keep it. You think of the list you could write: oversight clauses, community liaisons, inspection schedules, enforcement funding. You want to be precise; you want to be fast."
    "The decision is not simply about contracts or pride. It is about what kind of town Saltwick will be when the storms come next year — a town that accepted help and kept its hands on"
    "the wheel, a town that let outside speed rewrite its coast, or a town that found a third way and kept its people at the center while inviting the resources they needed."
    "The quay hums with low voices, the harbor bell rings once like a long breath. You feel the momentum you've built as a bright, rising thing: teams, seedlings, votes, and a town's cautious hope. The tension"
    "is not bleak; it lifts you toward a choice that could knit speed and care together if you can steer it rightly."
    hide ivo_calder
    hide maya_maren
    hide celine_harrow

    scene bg ch5_4001e7_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Rise to a hopeful, open chord]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant thunder, not threatening, more like a drumbeat pushing the scene forward]
    "You inhale. The town waits. The options collect in your chest like possible tides."

    menu:
        "Refuse Celine's contractors — we keep it community-led.":
            jump chapter6
        "Accept Celine's funding and contractors under municipal terms.":
            jump chapter13
        "Demand hybrid oversight — accept funds only with community enforcement.":
            jump chapter6
